# 2 Samuel 19–21: David's return to Jerusalem, Shimei's pardon, Mephibosheth's
# vindication, Barzillai's farewell, Judah-Israel tribal dispute, Sheba's rebellion
# and suppression by the wise woman of Abel, Gibeonite blood-guilt and its resolution.
# mkt-original linguistic commentary.

CH19 = {
    # v23 already present
    "1": "<p><em>Va-yuggad le-Yoav: hinneh ha-melekh bokheh va-yit'abbel al-Avshalom</em> — &ldquo;And it was told to Joab: behold, the king is weeping and mourning for Absalom.&rdquo; The Hophal passive <em>yuggad</em> (it was told) maintains narrator anonymity about the informant. <em>Bokheh va-yit'abbel</em> (weeping and mourning) combines the physical act (<em>bakhah</em>, cry) with the formal ritual state (<em>evel</em>, mourning) — David is in grief and in the formal state of one observing mourning simultaneously.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>Va-tehi ha-teshu'ah ba-yom ha-hu le-evel</em> — &ldquo;And the victory on that day was turned into mourning.&rdquo; The wordplay of <em>teshu'ah</em> (victory, deliverance) and <em>evel</em> (mourning) in the same verse expresses the day's paradox: military success and personal catastrophe simultaneously. <em>Ki-shama ha-am ba-yom ha-hu lemor: nit'atzev ha-melekh al-beno</em> — the people heard that the king was grieving (<em>nit'atzev</em>, Niphal of <em>atsav</em>, to be pained, grieved) for his son.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>Va-yitganev ha-am ba-yom ha-hu la-vo ha-ir</em> — &ldquo;And the people stole (<em>hitganev</em>, Hithpael of <em>ganav</em>) into the city that day.&rdquo; The Hithpael of <em>ganav</em> — the same root used for Absalom &ldquo;stealing the hearts&rdquo; of Israel (15:6) — now describes the victorious army slipping into the city like defeated men. The semantic inversion is pointed: the army that should enter in triumph enters in shame. <em>Ka-asher yitganev ha-am hanikklamim be-nusam ba-milchamah</em> — as people who are ashamed and have fled in battle sneak away.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>Ve-ha-melekh kissa et-panav</em> — &ldquo;And the king covered his face.&rdquo; The gesture of covering the face (<em>kassa et-panav</em>) is the posture of grief that withdraws from public view. <em>Va-yiz'aq ha-melekh qol gadol: beni Avshalom, Avshalom beni beni</em> — the repeated cry <em>beni</em> (my son) — five times in this verse and the preceding chapter — encodes grief in repeated grammatical units that resist rational processing.</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Vayavo Yoav el-ha-melekh ha-bayit vayomer</em> — Joab's confrontation with David. His speech (vv. 5–7) is the bluntest address to a king in the Succession Narrative. <em>Hevoshta ha-yom et-penei kol-avadekhah</em> — &ldquo;you have today shamed the faces of all your servants.&rdquo; <em>Hevoshta</em> (Hiphil of <em>bosh</em>, to be ashamed/put to shame) — to shame another's face was to publicly negate their honor, the most serious social harm in ancient Near Eastern culture.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>Le-ahavah et-sone'ekha ule-sno et-ohavekhah</em> — &ldquo;by loving those who hate you and hating those who love you.&rdquo; Joab's chiastic accusation expresses the inversion of proper relational logic: David loves his enemies (Absalom who tried to kill him) and hates his friends (the army that saved him). <em>Ki higgadta ha-yom ki ein-lekha sarim va-avadim</em> — &ldquo;for you have declared today that commanders and servants are nothing to you.&rdquo;</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>Ve-attah qum tze ve-dabber al-lev avadekhah</em> — Joab's command to David: &ldquo;rise, go out and speak to the heart (<em>al-lev</em>) of your servants.&rdquo; The phrase <em>dibber al-lev</em> (speak to the heart) is the idiom for comfort and reassurance — it appears in Gen 50:21 (Joseph comforting his brothers), Isa 40:2 (YHWH comforting Israel), and Ruth 2:13. Joab frames a political ultimatum in the rhetoric of pastoral care.</p>",
    "8": "<p><em>Va-yaqom ha-melekh vayeshev ba-sha'ar</em> — David's obedience: he rises and sits in the gate (<em>sha'ar</em>) — the judicial-civic space. <em>Va-yagidu le-khol-ha-am lemor: hinneh ha-melekh yoshev ba-sha'ar</em> — the announcement of the king's presence in the gate draws all the people before him. The gate-session is the king's performance of his judicial role — exactly the role Absalom had usurped in 15:2.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>Ve-khol-ha-am hayah nadan be-khol shivtei Yisra'el lemor</em> — &ldquo;And all the people were disputing among all the tribes of Israel.&rdquo; <em>Nadan</em> (Niphal participle of <em>don/din</em>, to quarrel, contend) — the tribes in contention with one another. The dispute (vv. 9–15) is the formal return-negotiation between David and the tribal leadership — a political process, not merely a personal restoration.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>Ve-Avshalom asher mashachnu alenu met ba-milchamah</em> — the people's acknowledgment that Absalom, whom they anointed (<em>mashachnu</em>, Qal of <em>mashach</em>, anoint) over themselves, is dead in battle. <em>Ve-attah lammah attem machasherim lehashiv et-ha-melekh</em> — &ldquo;and now why are you silent about bringing the king back?&rdquo; <em>Machasherim</em> (Hiphil participle of <em>charash</em>, be silent) — the accusation that the tribal leadership was slow to act on the political necessity.</p>",
    "11": "<p><em>Ve-ha-melekh David shalach el-Tzadoq ve-el-Evyatar ha-kohanim lemor</em> — David's direct outreach to the Judahite elders through the priests. <em>Dibberu el-ziqnei Yehudah lemor: maddua tihyu acharonim le-hashiv et-ha-melekh el-beito</em> — &ldquo;why are you last to bring the king back to his house?&rdquo; David appeals to tribal pride: Judah, his own tribe, should be leading the restoration, not following.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>Achai attem atzmai u-vesari attem</em> — &ldquo;you are my brothers; you are my bone and my flesh.&rdquo; The kinship formula <em>atzmi u-vesari</em> (my bone and my flesh) is the language of covenant kinship — it appears in Gen 2:23 (Adam's recognition of Eve), Gen 29:14 (Laban's recognition of Jacob), and Judg 9:2. David deploys the tribal bond as the basis for Judah's special obligation.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>Ve-le-Amasa tomeru: halo atzmi u-vesari attah</em> — David's offer to Amasa: &ldquo;are you not my bone and my flesh?&rdquo; — the kinship formula applied to Absalom's former general (David's nephew). The appointment of Amasa to replace Joab (<em>koh ya'aseh li elohim ve-kho yosif im-lo tihyeh sar-tzava lefanai kol-ha-yamim tachat Yoav</em> — may God do so to me if you are not commander before me instead of Joab) is politically calculated: winning over Absalom's former commander consolidates the restoration while punishing Joab for killing Absalom against David's command.</p>",
    "14": "<p><em>Va-yat levav kol-ish Yehudah ke-ish echad</em> — &ldquo;And he bent the heart of all the men of Judah as one man.&rdquo; <em>Vayat</em> (Hiphil of <em>natah</em>, to incline, bend) — David's outreach bent the hearts — a deliberate contrast with Absalom's <em>vayignov</em> (stealing) of hearts (15:6). David uses legitimate persuasion through kinship appeal; Absalom used deceptive seduction. <em>Ke-ish echad</em> (as one man) is the formula of unified collective resolve.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>Va-yavo ha-melekh ad-ha-Yarden</em> — David's arrival at the Jordan for the formal return crossing. The Jordan-crossing in both directions frames the exile narrative: crossing east was departure (15:23), crossing back west is restoration. <em>Ve-Yehudah ba le-Gilgal la-lekhet liqrat ha-melekh</em> — Judah came to Gilgal to escort the king. Gilgal was the ancient entry-point to the land (Josh 4–5) — the first camp after Jordan-crossing. The choice of Gilgal as meeting-place invokes the conquest entry as a template for David's return.</p>",
    "16": "<p><em>Va-yemaher Shim'i ben-Gera ben-ha-Yemini asher mi-Bachurim</em> — Shimei's rapid descent. <em>Vayemaher</em> (Piel of <em>mahar</em>, hurry) signals his awareness of danger. <em>Ve-itto eleph ish mi-Vinyamin</em> — a thousand Benjaminite men with him. The number signals political weight: Shimei arrives not alone but with a tribal contingent, framing his submission as a representative act.</p>",
    "17": "<p><em>Ve-Tziva na'ar beit Sha'ul ve-chamisha esrei banav ve-esrim avadav itto</em> — Ziba with fifteen sons and twenty servants. Ziba's presence at the return-crossing alongside Shimei creates a confrontation that will force the Mephibosheth question back onto David's agenda.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>Va-ya'avru ha-neshel la-a'avir et-beit ha-melekh</em> — they crossed the ford (<em>neshel</em>, a shallow crossing point) to transport the royal household. Shimei fell before the king as he was about to cross the Jordan, prostrating himself in the petition posture.</p>",
    "19": "<p><em>Vayomer el-ha-melekh: al-yachshov li adoni avon</em> — &ldquo;Let not my lord the king reckon iniquity to me.&rdquo; <em>Al-yachshov</em> (jussive of <em>chashav</em>, reckon, impute) with the negative is the standard formula for requesting non-imputation of guilt — the conceptual vocabulary of Ps 32:2 (<em>lo yachshov-lo YHWH avon</em>). <em>Al-tizkor asher he'ava avdekha</em> — do not remember (<em>zakar</em>) what your servant did wrong. The pairing of <em>chashav</em> (impute) and <em>zakar</em> (remember) covers both legal accounting and personal memory.</p>",
    "20": "<p><em>Ki yada avdekha ki anokhi chatati</em> — &ldquo;for your servant knows that I have sinned.&rdquo; <em>Yada</em> here is not merely intellectual acknowledgment but recognized moral knowledge that carries legal force. Shimei's admission of sin (<em>chatati</em>) is the formal confession that activates the possibility of royal forgiveness. <em>Ve-hinneh bati ha-yom rishon le-khol-beit Yosef la-redet liqrat adoni ha-melekh</em> — being the first of the house of Joseph (northern tribes) to come down to meet the king.</p>",
    "21": "<p><em>Vaya'an Avishai ben-Tzeruyah vayomer: hatahat zot lo yumat Shim'i ki qillel et-meshiach YHWH</em> — Abishai's demand for Shimei's execution: <em>meshiach YHWH</em> (anointed of YHWH) — the theological designation of the king as YHWH's anointed one whose person is sacred. Cursing the <em>meshiach YHWH</em> was a capital offense under ancient Israelite law; Abishai's citation is legally correct, even as David overrides it.</p>",
    "22": "<p><em>Vayomer David: mah-li va-lakhem benei Tzeruyah ki-tihyu li ha-yom le-satan</em> — David's rebuke: <em>le-satan</em> (as an adversary/accuser) — <em>satan</em> as a legal adversary who brings accusations before a court. This is not the later cosmic adversary but its legal root. <em>Ha-yom le-satan</em> (as an adversary today) signals that on the day of the king's return, executing Shimei would inaugurate the restored reign with blood, not mercy.</p>",
    "24": "<p><em>U-Mephiboshet ben-Sha'ul yarad liqrat ha-melekh</em> — Mephibosheth's descent to meet the king. <em>Ve-lo asah raglav ve-lo asah sephato ve-et-begadav lo kibbes mi-yom lekhet ha-melekh ad-ha-yom asher-ba be-shalom</em> — he had not dressed his feet (<em>raglav</em>), not trimmed his beard (<em>sephato</em>), and not washed his clothes (<em>kibbes</em>) from the day the king left until he returned in peace. The three neglected personal-care acts are the marks of someone observing the full mourning state for David's exile.</p>",
    "25": "<p><em>Va-yehi ki-va Yerushalaim liqrat ha-melekh vayomer lo ha-melekh: lammah lo-halahhta itti Mephiboshet</em> — David's direct question: why did you not go with me? <em>Lammah lo-halakhta itti</em> (why did you not go with me?) is the same loyalty-test question Absalom asked Hushai (16:17) — testing whether the failure of accompaniment was choice or circumstance.</p>",
    "26": "<p><em>Vayomer: adoni ha-melekh avdi rimmani</em> — &ldquo;My lord the king, my servant deceived me.&rdquo; <em>Rimmani</em> (Piel perfect of <em>ramah</em>, deceive, trick) — the same verb used for Jacob's deception of Isaac. Mephibosheth's counter-narrative: Ziba deceived him. <em>Ki amar avdekha achboshshah-li ha-chamor ve-erkav alav ve-elekh el-ha-melekh ki pissea avdekha</em> — he requested a donkey to ride because he is lame (<em>pissea</em>), but Ziba did not saddle it.</p>",
    "27": "<p><em>Va-yeshlel bi be-avdekha el-adoni ha-melekh</em> — &ldquo;And he slandered me (<em>yeshlel</em>, from <em>ragal</em>, to slander, go about as a spy) to my lord the king.&rdquo; <em>Va-adoni ha-melekh ke-malakh ha-elohim</em> — the comparison of the king to an angel of God (also at 14:17; 16:17) places the burden of discernment on David's reputed wisdom.</p>",
    "28": "<p><em>Ki kol-beit avi lo-hayu ki im-anshei-mavet la-adoni ha-melekh</em> — &ldquo;all my father's house were nothing but dead men before my lord the king.&rdquo; <em>Anshei-mavet</em> (men of death/doomed men) — all of Saul's household would have been executed except for David's <em>chesed</em>. <em>Va-tasem et-avdekha be-toch okhlei shulchanekha</em> — and you set your servant among those who eat at your table — the covenant adoption formula of ch. 9 invoked again.</p>",
    "29": "<p><em>Vayomer lo ha-melekh: lammah tedabber od devarekha</em> — David's response: why do you keep speaking? <em>Amarti: attah ve-Tziva tachlequ et-ha-sadeh</em> — &ldquo;you and Ziba shall divide the field.&rdquo; David's compromise verdict — splitting the inheritance between Ziba and Mephibosheth — implicitly acknowledges that his original grant to Ziba (16:4) was made on insufficient evidence, but he lacks enough confidence in Mephibosheth's counter-narrative to fully reverse it.</p>",
    "30": "<p><em>Vayomer Mephiboshet el-ha-melekh: gam et-ha-kol yiqach</em> — Mephibosheth's response: &ldquo;let him take everything.&rdquo; <em>Gam et-ha-kol yiqach</em> (even let him take everything) — the renunciation of the property claim in favor of the king's shalom: <em>acharei asher-ba adoni ha-melekh be-shalom el-beito</em> (after my lord the king has come home in peace). Whether interpreted as genuine loyalty, political wisdom, or resignation, the renunciation echoes the legal waiver-of-claim gesture.</p>",
    "31": "<p><em>Ve-Barzillai ha-Gil'adi yarad mi-Rogelim va-ya'avor et-ha-Yarden im-ha-melekh le-shal'cho min-ha-Yarden</em> — Barzillai the Gileadite escorting David across the Jordan. The verb <em>le-shal'cho</em> (to send him off/escort him) is the farewell-escort idiom — the same idiom used for honorable departures in Gen 18:16 and Ruth. Barzillai is very old (<em>ben-shemonim shanah</em>, eighty years old) and very wealthy.</p>",
    "32": "<p><em>Ve-hu kilkel et-ha-melekh be-shivto be-Machanayim</em> — Barzillai had supported David during the Mahanaim exile (<em>kilkel</em>, Pilel of <em>kul</em>, to sustain, provision). <em>Ki ish gadol hu me'od</em> — for he was a very great man. The portrait of Barzillai — old, wealthy, great — depicts a man at the pinnacle of social position who gave material support to a fallen king at personal risk.</p>",
    "33": "<p><em>Vayomer ha-melekh el-Barzillai: attah avor itti ve-kilkalti otekha imadi vi-Yerushalaim</em> — David's invitation: cross over with me and I will sustain you (<em>kilkalti</em>, the same verb Barzillai used for his provisioning of David). The reciprocal use of <em>kilkel</em> creates a verbal contract of mutual provision.</p>",
    "34": "<p><em>Vayomer Barzillai el-ha-melekh: kamah yemei shenei chayai ki-e'eleh im-ha-melekh Yerushalaim</em> — &ldquo;how many years of my life remain that I should go up with the king to Jerusalem?&rdquo; Barzillai's self-assessment — <em>ben-shemonim shanah anokhi ha-yom</em> (I am eighty years old today) — frames his refusal as a practical assessment of what old age cannot enjoy, not ingratitude.</p>",
    "35": "<p><em>Ha-eda od ha-tov ve-ha-ra'</em> — &ldquo;can I still discern good from evil?&rdquo; The question inverts the formula applied to the king as ideal judge (14:17, <em>lishmo'a ha-tov ve-ha-ra'</em>). Barzillai admits the faculties of wisdom and pleasure have diminished. <em>Im-yita'em avdekha et-asher yokhal ve-et-asher eshte im-eshma od be-qol sharim ve-sharot</em> — can I taste what I eat and drink? Can I hear the voice of singers and singing women?</p>",
    "36": "<p><em>Me'at ya'avor avdekha et-ha-Yarden im-ha-melekh</em> — &ldquo;your servant will go a short way (<em>me'at</em>) with the king over the Jordan.&rdquo; The partial escort reflects Barzillai's compromise: accompany David to the Jordan but not to Jerusalem. <em>Ve-lammah yigmel ha-melekh li ha-gemul ha-zeh</em> — why should the king recompense me with this recompense?</p>",
    "37": "<p><em>Yashuv na avdekha ve-amut be-iri im-qever avi ve-immi</em> — Barzillai's request: let me die in my city, near the graves of my father and mother. The desire to die in one's ancestral city and be buried near parents reflects the ancient Near Eastern attachment to ancestral burial sites. <em>Ve-hinneh avdekha Kimham ya'avor im-adoni ha-melekh</em> — but here is your servant Chimham; let him cross with my lord the king.</p>",
    "38": "<p><em>Vayomer ha-melekh: itti ya'avor Kimham ve-ani e'eseh-lo et-ha-tov asher-tiv beineykhah alai</em> — David grants the substitute: Chimham (likely Barzillai's son) will cross with David and receive the promised favor. The phrase <em>asher-tiv beineykhah alai</em> (whatever you desire from me) is an open-ended royal gift formula.</p>",
    "39": "<p><em>Va-yishaq ha-melekh le-Varzillai va-yevarekhehu va-yashov limqomo</em> — David kissed Barzillai (the kiss of formal farewell-honor) and blessed him, and Barzillai returned to his place. The departure of Barzillai with his blessing is one of the Succession Narrative's most affecting scenes: the wealthy old man who asked for nothing except permission to die at home.</p>",
    "40": "<p><em>Va-ya'avor ha-melekh ha-Gilgal ve-Kimham avar imo</em> — David crossing to Gilgal with Chimham. <em>Ve-khol-am Yehudah he'eviru et-ha-melekh ve-gam chtzi am Yisra'el</em> — all the people of Judah crossed the king over, and also half the people of Israel. The half-and-half division foreshadows the tribal dispute that immediately follows.</p>",
    "41": "<p><em>Ve-hinneh kol-anshei Yisra'el ba'u el-ha-melekh va-yomeru el-ha-melekh: maddua genevekhah achinu anshei Yehudah va-ya'aviru et-ha-melekh</em> — &ldquo;why have our brothers, the men of Judah, stolen you (<em>genevekhah</em>) and brought the king over?&rdquo; The northern tribes' accusation uses <em>ganav</em> (steal) — the third deployment of this root in the Succession Narrative (15:6, 19:3, now 19:41). The tribal jealousy that will eventually split the kingdom (1 Kgs 12) appears here in embryo.</p>",
    "42": "<p><em>Vaya'an kol-ish Yehudah al-ish Yisra'el: ki-qarov ha-melekh elai</em> — Judah's answer: because the king is my kinsman (<em>qarov</em>). The kinship argument is both the claim and the problem — Judah asserts special access to the king on the basis of tribal proximity. <em>Ve-lammah zeh charah lakhem al-ha-davar ha-zeh</em> — why be angry about this? We ate nothing of the king's; was any gift given to us?</p>",
    "43": "<p><em>Vaya'an ish Yisra'el et-ish Yehudah vayomer: eser yadot li ba-melekh</em> — the northern rejoinder: &ldquo;I have ten shares in the king.&rdquo; <em>Eser yadot</em> (ten hands/shares) reflects the ten-tribe majority's claim to greater proportional stake in the king. <em>Ve-gam be-David ani mimkha</em> — &ldquo;and also in David I am more than you.&rdquo; The tribal arithmetic dispute — ten vs. one, proportional representation vs. kinship priority — is a constitutional argument about the nature of Davidic kingship that has no resolution within the Succession Narrative.</p>",
}

CH20 = {
    # v1 already present
    "2": "<p><em>Va-ya'al kol-ish Yisra'el me-acharei David acharei Sheva ben-Bikhri</em> — the northern tribes' departure: <em>ya'al</em> (go up) after Sheba. <em>Ve-anshei Yehudah davqu be-malekham min-ha-Yarden ve-ad Yerushalaim</em> — the men of Judah clung (<em>davaq</em>, the covenant-loyalty verb of Ruth 1:14 and Gen 2:24) to their king from the Jordan to Jerusalem. The contrast between northern departure and Judahite adhesion repeats the tribal structure of the Absalom revolt.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>Va-yavo David el-beito Yerushalaim vayiqach ha-melekh et-eser nashim pilagshim asher hinnich lishemor ha-bayit</em> — David's arrival in Jerusalem and the disposition of the ten concubines. <em>Va-yittenem be-veit mishmereth</em> — he put them in a house of custody (<em>mishmereth</em>), provided for them, but did not go to them. <em>Va-tihnah tzerurot ad yom motanen almanut chayot</em> — they were kept shut up, living in widowhood (<em>almanut</em>) until the day of their death. The women who suffered the public violation become permanent victims of the political crisis they did not choose.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>Vayomer ha-melekh el-Amasa: zaq-li et-anshei Yehudah shloshet yamim</em> — David's mobilization order to Amasa: muster the men of Judah within three days. The three-day timeline is a tactical deadline — Sheba's rebellion must be suppressed before it can consolidate. <em>Ve-attah po amed</em> — and you, stand here (be here with the assembled force when the time comes).</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Va-yelekh Amasa liqbots et-Yehudah va-yo'acher mi-ha-moed asher ya'ad lo</em> — Amasa went to muster Judah but was delayed (<em>yo'acher</em>, Hiphil of <em>achar</em>, be late) beyond the set time. The delay is narratively significant: Amasa's inability to mobilize quickly enough gives Joab the pretext to supersede him. The political calculation of replacing Joab with Amasa begins to unravel at the first test.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>Vayomer David el-Avishai: attah yare' lanu Sheva ben-Bikhri</em> — David's assessment: Sheba will do more harm than Absalom did. <em>Qach et-avdei adonekha ve-radaph acharav</em> — take your lord's servants (Joab's professional force, the Cherethites and Pelethites) and pursue him, lest he find fortified cities and escape. The decision effectively reinstates Joab's force under Abishai's nominal command.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>Va-yetze'u acharav anshei Yoav ve-ha-Kerethi ve-ha-Pelethi ve-khol-ha-gibborim</em> — the three units following Abishai: Joab's men, the Cherethites and Pelethites (royal guard), and the mighty men (<em>gibborim</em>). The composite force is the professional standing army that has remained loyal throughout the Absalom crisis.</p>",
    "8": "<p><em>Hem im-ha-even ha-gedolah asher be-Givon va-Amasa ba liqratam</em> — Amasa coming to meet them at the great stone in Gibeon. <em>Ve-Yoav chagor milbasho asher livsho ve-alav chagor cherev metzumedeth al-motnav be-ta'aroh</em> — Joab girded with his military garment, with a sword strapped at his hip in its sheath. The detail of Joab's sword setup — the sheath that will allow the blade to fall out when he bends forward — is the narrator's surgical preparation for the murder about to occur.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>Vayomer Yoav le-Amasa: hashalom attah achi</em> — &ldquo;Is it well with you, my brother?&rdquo; Joab's greeting uses the kinship term <em>achi</em> (my brother) — both are David's nephews, making them actual cousins. <em>Shalom</em> before the murder is a bitter irony: the peace-greeting as cover for violence. <em>Va-tochaz yad-Yamin Yoav bi-zeqan Amasa le-nashaq-lo</em> — and Joab's right hand took Amasa by the beard to kiss him. Seizing the beard before a kiss was the gesture of greeting-intimacy; here it positions the victim for the killing blow.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>Ve-Amasa lo-nishmar ba-cherev asher be-yad Yoav</em> — &ldquo;and Amasa did not watch (<em>nishmar</em>, Niphal of <em>shamar</em>) the sword that was in Joab's hand.&rdquo; <em>Va-yakkehuh bah el-ha-chomeish va-yishpokh me'av artzah ve-lo-shanah-lo</em> — he struck him in the belly (<em>chomeish</em>) and poured out his bowels to the ground without striking a second time. The single blow to the abdomen — different from Joab's two-blow killing of Abner (3:27) — is narrated with clinical economy. Joab has now killed two of David's designated commanders, establishing a pattern of unsanctioned eliminations that David cannot address.</p>",
    "11": "<p><em>Ve-ish echad min-na'arei Yoav amad alav vayomer: mi asher chaphetz be-Yoav u-mi asher le-David acharei Yoav</em> — one of Joab's men stood over Amasa's body rallying the troops: &ldquo;whoever favors Joab and whoever is for David, after Joab!&rdquo; The juxtaposition of Joab and David as co-loyalties is precisely the political problem: Joab has made himself indispensable by eliminating the alternatives.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>Ve-Amasa mitgollel ba-dam be-tokh ha-mesilah</em> — Amasa rolling in blood (<em>mitgollel</em>, Hithpoel of <em>galal</em>, to roll) in the middle of the road. <em>Va-yar ha-ish ki-amad kol-ha-am vayaseg et-Amasa min-ha-mesilah ha-sadeh</em> — seeing everyone stopping to look at the body, the man dragged Amasa from the road to the field. The practical problem of a corpse blocking the march is handled with narrative matter-of-factness that heightens the horror.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>Ka-asher hosar min-ha-mesilah avar kol-ish acharei Yoav lirdoph acharei Sheva ben-Bikhri</em> — once the body was off the road, all the men went after Joab to pursue Sheba. The narrative's restoration of focus to the military mission after Amasa's murder reflects the Succession Narrative's repeated pattern: Joab commits an extrajudicial killing and immediately leads the army back to its task, making his crimes politically unaddressable.</p>",
    "14": "<p><em>Va-ya'avor be-khol shivtei Yisra'el el-Avel u-Veit-Ma'akha ve-khol-ha-Beirim</em> — Sheba's march through all the tribes to Abel-beth-maacah. <em>Avel</em> (Abel) may mean meadow or mourning; <em>beit-Ma'akha</em> (house of Maacah) was a northern city with connections to the Aramaean kingdom of Maacah. Its northern border location makes it Sheba's natural refuge — far from David's base and connected to non-Davidic power.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>Va-yavo'u va-yatzuru alav be-Avel Beit-Ma'akha</em> — they besieged him in Abel-beth-maacah. <em>Va-yishpeku solelah el-ha-ir va-ta'amod ba-chel</em> — they cast up a siege-ramp (<em>solelah</em>) against the city and it stood against the outer wall (<em>chel</em>). The <em>solelah</em> (siege mound/ramp) is the standard ancient Near Eastern siege technique — documented in Assyrian military reliefs and at Lachish — used to raise the attackers to wall-top level for assault.</p>",
    "16": "<p><em>Va-tiqra ishah chakhamah min-ha-ir: shim'u shim'u imru na el-Yoav qerav ad-henna ve-adabberah elekhah</em> — the wise woman (<em>ishah chakhamah</em>) calling from the city. This is the second <em>ishah chakhamah</em> in the Succession Narrative (cf. 14:2). The pattern of wise women who prevent unnecessary violence is a distinctive feature of 2 Samuel's narrative theology.</p>",
    "17": "<p><em>Va-yiqrav eleha vattomer ha-ishah: ha-attah Yoav vayomer ani</em> — the woman's direct identification of the general before negotiating is a demonstration of authority — she speaks to the commander himself, not through intermediaries.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>Va-tedabber lemor: dabber yedabberu ba-rishonah lemor: sha'ol yish'alu be-Avel ve-ken hitemmu</em> — &ldquo;they used to say in former times: let them ask at Abel, and so they would conclude the matter.&rdquo; The woman invokes Abel's reputation as a place of wise counsel — a city known for resolving disputes without violence. Her appeal to tradition frames the siege as an attack on a resource Israel has historically relied on.</p>",
    "19": "<p><em>Anokhi shelumet emunei Yisra'el attah mevaqesh lehamit ir ve-em be-Yisra'el</em> — &ldquo;I am one of the peaceable and faithful of Israel; you seek to destroy a city and a mother in Israel.&rdquo; <em>Ir ve-em be-Yisra'el</em> (a city and a mother in Israel) is a unique phrase — the city as <em>em</em> (mother) is the idiom for a major settlement with dependent villages (cf. Num 21:25). The woman frames the siege as matricide.</p>",
    "20": "<p><em>Vaya'an Yoav vayomer: chalilah chalilah li im-evalla ve-im-ashchit</em> — Joab's denial: <em>chalilah</em> (far be it from me) — the strong negation formula (cf. Gen 44:7; 1 Sam 14:45). The doubled <em>chalilah chalilah</em> intensifies the denial. Joab denies the intent to destroy — he only wants Sheba ben-Bikhri.</p>",
    "21": "<p><em>Lo-khen ha-davar ki ish me-har Ephraim Sheva ben-Bikhri shemo nasa yado ba-melekh be-David</em> — &ldquo;not so; but a man from the hill country of Ephraim, Sheba ben-Bikhri, has raised his hand against the king.&rdquo; <em>Nasa yado</em> (raised his hand against) is the idiom of rebellion (cf. 1 Kgs 11:26 for Jeroboam's rebellion). The identification of Sheba as the only target narrows the demand to one person — which is the opening the woman needed.</p>",
    "22": "<p><em>Va-tavo ha-ishah el-kol-ha-am be-chokhmata</em> — the woman going to all the people with her wisdom. <em>Be-chokhmata</em> (in her wisdom) — the noun <em>chokmah</em> used adverbially marks her method. <em>Va-yikhretu et-rosh Sheva ben-Bikhri va-yashlikhu el-Yoav</em> — they cut off Sheba's head and threw it to Joab. <em>Va-yitqa ba-shofar vayafutzu me-al-ha-ir ish le-ohalav</em> — Joab sounded the trumpet and they dispersed from the city, each to his tent. The summary efficiency — one woman's wisdom, one severed head, one trumpet blast — is a pointed contrast to the months of civil war in the Absalom revolt.</p>",
    "23": "<p><em>Ve-Yoav el-kol-ha-tzava Yisra'el</em> — Joab over all the army of Israel. The cabinet list concluding ch. 20 mirrors the one in 8:15–18, framing the restoration as a return to the pre-revolt administrative order. Joab is back in his position — despite having killed Absalom against direct orders and killed Amasa extrajudicially — because there is no one else capable of commanding the army. The political realities of the Davidic state make Joab's accountability impossible within David's lifetime (cf. 1 Kgs 2:5–6).</p>",
    "24": "<p><em>Ve-Adoram al-ha-mas</em> — Adoram over the forced labor (<em>mas</em>). The <em>mas</em> (labor levy, corvée) is a regular institution of David's administrative apparatus — the use of conscripted labor for building projects. <em>Ve-Yehoshaphat ben-Achilud ha-mazkir</em> — Jehoshaphat the son of Ahilud, the recorder (<em>mazkir</em>, one who remembers/records — the royal secretary).</p>",
    "25": "<p><em>Ve-Sheva sopher</em> — Sheva (different from Sheba ben-Bikhri) was the secretary (<em>sopher</em>, scribe). <em>Ve-Tzadoq ve-Evyatar kohanim</em> — Zadok and Abiathar as priests. The dual-priesthood that ran through the Absalom crisis remains intact. <em>Ve-gam Ira ha-Ya'iri hayah kohen le-David</em> — and also Ira the Jairite was a priest to David — an additional priestly appointment suggesting the expansion of the Davidic cult administration.</p>",
}

CH21 = {
    # v1 and v17 already present
    "2": "<p><em>Va-yiqra ha-melekh la-Giv'onim vayomer aleyhem</em> — David summoned the Gibeonites. The Gibeonites were not part of Israel but of the remnant of the Amorites (<em>ha-Emori</em>); Israel had sworn to spare them (Josh 9:15–20), but Saul had tried to destroy them &ldquo;in his zeal for Israel and Judah.&rdquo; The failure to name Saul's specific act may reflect lost narrative or deliberate vagueness; what matters legally is that a <em>shevuat YHWH</em> (oath of YHWH) had been violated.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>Vayomer David el-ha-Giv'onim: mah e'eseh lakhem u-vammah achapper</em> — David's question: &ldquo;what shall I do for you and how shall I make atonement (<em>achapper</em>, Piel of <em>kapar</em>, to make atonement)?&rdquo; The use of <em>kipper</em> for the remediation of the blood-guilt is significant: this is not merely political negotiation but covenantal atonement — the language of the cult applied to a civil-legal crisis. <em>U-varekhu et-nachalat YHWH</em> — that you may bless the inheritance of YHWH — David's goal is restoration of divine blessing over the land.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>Vayomeru lo ha-Giv'onim: ein-lanu kesef ve-zahav im-Sha'ul ve-im-beito</em> — the Gibeonites' refusal of silver and gold: <em>ein-lanu</em> (we have no claim for) — the rejection of financial compensation. <em>Ve-ein-lanu ish le-hamit be-Yisra'el</em> — they are not claiming general blood-vengeance. Their demand will be specific: particular lives of Saul's house for particular lives taken.</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Vayomeru el-ha-melekh: ha-ish asher kilanu ve-asher dimmah-lanu nishmednu</em> — &ldquo;the man who consumed us and who devised to exterminate us.&rdquo; <em>Kilanu</em> (Piel of <em>kalah</em>, consume, annihilate) and <em>dimmah-lanu</em> (devised against us, Piel of <em>damah</em>, plan) — the double verb of planned annihilation establishes the severity of Saul's crime. The crime was calculated (<em>dimmah</em>), making the blood-guilt especially serious.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>Yuttan-lanu shiv'ah anashim mi-banav ve-hoqa'anum la-YHWH be-Giv'ah Sha'ul bachir YHWH</em> — &ldquo;let seven men of his sons be given to us, and we will impale them (<em>hoqa'anum</em>, Hiphil of <em>yaqa'</em>, hang/impale/expose) before YHWH in Gibeah of Saul.&rdquo; <em>Hoqa'</em> as a form of execution/exposure was used for the ultimate disgrace; it appears in Num 25:4 for the Baal-peor sinners. The number seven (<em>shiv'ah</em>) is the sacred completion number in ritual contexts.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>Va-yachmol ha-melekh al-Mephiboshet ben-Yehonatan ben-Sha'ul</em> — the king had compassion (<em>yachmol</em>, Qal of <em>chamal</em>, spare, have compassion) on Mephibosheth son of Jonathan. <em>Al-shevuat YHWH asher beineyhem bein David u-vein Yehonatan ben-Sha'ul</em> — because of the oath of YHWH between them, between David and Jonathan. The protection of Mephibosheth from the Gibeonite demand is the direct application of the Jonathan covenant (1 Sam 18:3, 20:15–17). David protects Mephibosheth not from general compassion but from specific covenant obligation.</p>",
    "8": "<p><em>Va-yiqach ha-melekh et-shenei venei Ritzpah bat-Ayah</em> — the two sons of Rizpah: Armoni and Mephibosheth (a different Mephibosheth from Jonathan's son). <em>Ve-et-chamisha venei Mikhal bat-Sha'ul</em> — the MT reads Michal; 1 Sam 18:19 names Merab as Adriel's wife. The LXX and some manuscripts read Merab here, which is the lectio difficilior and more historically coherent reading.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>Va-yitnem be-yad ha-Giv'onim va-yoqi'um ba-har lifnei YHWH</em> — he gave them into the hands of the Gibeonites and they impaled them on the mountain before YHWH. <em>Ve-hem humtu bi-ymei katzir ba-rishonim bi-tchillat katzir se'orim</em> — they were put to death at the beginning of barley harvest. The harvest timing is significant: rain in the dry season was the divine sign (1 Sam 12:17) that YHWH's blessing was connected to covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>Va-tiqach Ritzpah bat-Ayah et-ha-saq va-tattehu lah el-ha-tzur mi-tchillat katzir ad nittakh mayim aleihem min-ha-shamayim</em> — Rizpah daughter of Aiah spread sackcloth on a rock for herself from the beginning of harvest until rain fell on them from heaven. The vigil of Rizpah — guarding the bodies of her sons from birds by day and beasts by night — is one of the most powerful maternal grief scenes in biblical literature. The sackcloth as mourning marker, her sustained presence as the guard that prevented the ultimate dishonor of the bodies being consumed.</p>",
    "11": "<p><em>Va-yuggad le-David et asher astha Ritzpah bat-Ayah pilegesh Sha'ul</em> — the report of Rizpah's vigil triggers David's action: he goes to collect the bones of Saul and Jonathan from Jabesh-gilead. The narrative connection between Rizpah's vigil and David's retrieval creates the theological point: proper burial that honors the dead is the human response that completes the atonement begun by the impalement.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>Va-yelekh David va-yiqach et-atzmot Sha'ul ve-et-atzmot Yehonatan beno me'et ba'alei Yavesh Gil'ad</em> — David retrieved the bones of Saul and Jonathan from the men of Jabesh-gilead, who had taken them from the wall of Beth-shan (1 Sam 31:11–13). The recovery honors both Saul (the anointed king David respected throughout his life) and Jonathan (the covenant friend). The care shown for proper burial of both enemies and friends reflects the ancient Near Eastern understanding that burial was a sacred obligation.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>Va-ya'al mi-sham et-atzmot Sha'ul ve-et-atzmot Yehonatan beno va-ya'aseph et-atzmot ha-muqa'im</em> — he brought up the bones of Saul and Jonathan and gathered the bones of the impaled men. The gathering of all the bones together — Saul, Jonathan, and the seven impaled men — for burial in the ancestral tomb formally closes the blood-guilt account. The reburial in the ancestral tomb restores the honor of the royal Saulide line after the public execution.</p>",
    "14": "<p><em>Va-yiqberu et-atzmot Sha'ul u-Yehonatan beno be-eretz Binyamin be-Tzel'ah be-qever Qish avi Sha'ul</em> — burial in Benjamin, in Zela, in the grave of Kish. The geographic specification (<em>eretz Binyamin</em>) returns the Saulide bones to their tribal territory and ancestral burial ground. <em>Va-ye'ater Elohim la-aretz acharei-khen</em> — and God was moved by entreaty (<em>ya'ater</em>, Niphal of <em>atar</em>, be entreated, be appeased) for the land after that. The verb marks the resolution of the divine anger — the famine ends because the blood-guilt has been properly atoned.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>Ve-thi od ha-milchamah la-Pelishtim el-Yisra'el va-yered David ve-avadav imo va-yilachamu et-ha-Pelishtim</em> — return of Philistine war. <em>Va-yiyga'ph David</em> — and David became weary (<em>yaga'</em>, to be exhausted, weary). The notice of David's weariness in battle is the first explicit statement of his physical limitations — marking the transition from David as warrior-king to David as commander-king who cannot personally fight.</p>",
    "16": "<p><em>Ve-Yishbi-Benov asher bi-yelide ha-Rapha</em> — Ishbi-benob who was among the descendants of the Rapha (<em>ha-Rapha</em>, the giant, the Rephaim). The Rephaim tradition — a pre-Israelite race of warriors of exceptional physical size — appears throughout the conquest narratives (Deut 3:11, Josh 12:4). <em>Va-yachashov lehakot et-David</em> — he thought (<em>chashav</em>, calculate) to strike David — a deliberate targeted attack on the king personally.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>Va-tehi acharei-khen od ha-milchamah be-Gov im-ha-Pelishtim az hikkah Sibbechai ha-Chushati et-Saph asher bi-yelide ha-Rapha</em> — at Gob, Sibbechai the Hushathite killed Saph, another Rephaim descendant. The series of giant-killings (vv. 18–22) — Sibbechai, Elhanan, Jonathan ben-Shimeah — documents the systematic elimination of Philistine warrior-heroes. Each killing is attributed to one of David's mighty men (<em>gibborim</em>), not to David himself — the transition from royal warrior to patron of warriors is complete.</p>",
    "19": "<p><em>Va-tehi od ha-milchamah be-Gov im-ha-Pelishtim va-yakh Elhanan ben-Ya'are-Oregim ha-Beit-ha-Lachmi et Golyat ha-Gitti</em> — Elhanan killed Goliath the Gittite. The text as it stands attributes a Goliath-killing to Elhanan, which creates the famous tension with 1 Sam 17 (where David kills Goliath). The parallel in 1 Chr 20:5 reads &ldquo;the brother of Goliath&rdquo; — a text-critical variant that attempts to resolve the apparent contradiction. Whether the chronicle is a correction or preserves a different tradition is debated.</p>",
    "20": "<p><em>Va-tehi od milchamah be-Gat va-yehi ish middon ve-etzba'otav shesh ve-shesh esrim ve-arba</em> — at Gath, a man of great stature with six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot, twenty-four digits total. <em>Va-yiledh gam-hu le-ha-Rapha</em> — he also was born to the Rapha. The precise enumeration of digits (<em>shesh ve-shesh esrim ve-arba</em>) is a narrative curiosity that the text records with ethnographic precision — the warrior's physical anomaly as a marker of Rephaim descent.</p>",
    "21": "<p><em>Va-yecharaph et-Yisra'el va-yakkehhu Yehonatan ben-Shime'ah achi David</em> — and when he taunted Israel, Jonathan son of Shimeah, David's brother, killed him. The verb <em>charaph</em> (taunt, reproach, defy) connects the Gittite giant to the Goliath narrative (1 Sam 17:10, 25–26, 36, 45 — the same root throughout): the taunting of Israel as a religious insult that required a champion to answer.</p>",
    "22": "<p><em>Arbah elleh yuldu la-Rapha ve-Gat va-yippelu be-yad David u-ve-yad avadav</em> — &ldquo;these four were born to the Rapha in Gath and they fell by the hand of David and by the hand of his servants.&rdquo; The summary formula — <em>yippelu be-yad David u-ve-yad avadav</em> — is the key closing statement: the victories belong to both David and his servants. The aging king who can no longer fight personally is credited with the victories won by his men — the covenant community's victories belong to its anointed head.</p>",
}

